----- DISASSEMBLED -----
.class public com.example.test/MyClass
.super java/lang/Object

.class_end
----- INPUT -----
; Tests that .package directive with '.' separator produces a warning.
; Input: .package com.example.test (using Java-style dots)
; Expected: Warning W-002 about using '.' as separator
; This proves:
;   1. Parser detects '.' in package name
;   2. Warning suggests using '/' instead (recommended for bytecode)
;   3. Package name is kept as-is in bytecode (dots are NOT converted)

.class public MyClass
.package com.example.test
.super java/lang/Object

.class_end
----- STDERR -----
[W-002] Warning: package name 'com.example.test' contains '.' separator
    ╭─[ test_data/rns_integration/rns_warn/package_with_dots.rns:10:10 ]
    │
 10 │ .package com.example.test
    │          ────────┬───────  
    │                  ╰───────── package 'com.example.test' uses '.' as separator
    │ 
    │ Help: If you intended Java-style package syntax, use '/' instead: 'com/example/test'
    │ 
    │ Note: In bytecode, package separators are represented as '/'. The '.' character is used in Java source syntax but will be kept as-is in the bytecode.
────╯
